<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,152,176]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis box="[199,314,152,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
—
</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hulebak, E. &amp; Poe, S. &amp; Ibanez, R. &amp; Williams, E. E." box="[343,580,151,176]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="5 - 10" refId="ref39107" refString="Hulebak, E., Poe, S., Ibanez, R., &amp; Williams, E. E. (2007) A striking new species of Anolis lizard (Squamata: Iguania) from Panama. Phyllomedusa, 6, 5 - 10." type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulebak 
<emphasis box="[444,492,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">et al</emphasis>
. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
in the course of describing 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hulebak, Poe, Ibanez, and Williams" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[887,1112,152,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Dactyloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kunayalae">
<emphasis box="[887,1112,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Dactyloa kunayalae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
suggested that it might be an ally of the Colombian 
<taxonomicName box="[409,509,189,212]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Dactyloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mirus">
<emphasis box="[409,509,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">D. mirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[566,685,188,212]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Dactyloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parrilis">
<emphasis box="[566,685,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">D. parrilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They noted that the three taxa share a unique morphology of the fourth toe, including few lamellae, indistinct toe pad, and especially long claw (see 
<figureCitation box="[1087,1153,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1080,1103]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,433,1055]" captionTargetId="figure-498@4.[151,1436,419,1059]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representation of Etheridge’s (1960) hypothesis of relationships for dactyloid lizards." pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1139,1153,223,247]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="in" value="1.0">1</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, E. E." box="[1189,1364,223,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 480" refId="ref43226" refString="Williams, E. E. (1963) Studies on South American anoles. Description of Anolis mirus, new species from Rio San Juan, Colombia, with comment on digital dilation and dewlap as generic and specific characters in the anoles. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard, 129, 463 - 480." type="journal article" year="1963">Williams, 1963</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
